Critical Bug Spotted — SQL Injection
A dangerous security vulnerability was hiding in plain sight inside the unreadable code. Readable code makes bugs easier to spot.

// DANGEROUS — never concatenate user input into SQL
db.execute("INSERT INTO users VALUES ('" + un + "', '" + pw + "', '" + em + "')");

// SAFE — use prepared statements
databaseConnection.execute("INSERT INTO users VALUES (?, ?, ?)", username, password, email);

Improved Java Code
class UserManager {
    private List<User> userList;
    private DatabaseConnection databaseConnection;

    public boolean addUser(String username, String password, String email) {
        if (!isValidUserInput(username, password, email)) return false;
        if (isUsernameTaken(username)) return false;
        User newUser = new User(username, password, email);
        userList.add(newUser);
        return saveUserToDatabase(newUser);
    }

    private boolean isValidUserInput(String username, String password, String email) {
        return username.length() >= 3
            && password.length() >= 8
            && email.contains('@');
    }

    private boolean isUsernameTaken(String username) {
        return userList.stream()
            .anyMatch(user -> user.getUsername().equals(username));
    }

    private boolean saveUserToDatabase(User user) {
        return databaseConnection.execute(
            "INSERT INTO users VALUES (?, ?, ?)",
            user.getUsername(), user.getPassword(), user.getEmail()
        );
    }

    public User findUserByUsername(String username) {
        return userList.stream()
            .filter(user -> user.getUsername().equals(username))
            .findFirst()
            .orElse(null);
    }
}

Issues I Missed That AI Found
•	SQL injection vulnerability — critical security bug hidden by unreadable variable names
•	Missing separation of concerns — validation, lookup, and save should be separate methods
•	Java stream() is more idiomatic than for-each loops for filtering

Exercise 2: Function Refactoring (Python)
Original Code
def process_orders(orders, inventory, customer_data):
    results = []
    total_revenue = 0
    error_orders = []
    for order in orders:
        item_id = order['item_id']
        quantity = order['quantity']
        customer_id = order['customer_id']
        if item_id not in inventory:
            error_orders.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'error': 'Item not in inventory'})
            continue
        if inventory[item_id]['quantity'] < quantity:
            error_orders.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'error': 'Insufficient quantity'})
            continue
        if customer_id not in customer_data:
            error_orders.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'error': 'Customer not found'})
            continue
        price = inventory[item_id]['price'] * quantity
        if customer_data[customer_id]['premium']:
            price = price * 0.9
        inventory[item_id]['quantity'] -= quantity
        shipping = 0
        if customer_data[customer_id]['location'] == 'domestic':
            if price < 50:
                shipping = 5.99
        else:
            shipping = 15.99
        tax = price * 0.08
        final_price = price + shipping + tax
        total_revenue += final_price
        results.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'final_price': final_price})
    return {'processed_orders': results, 'error_orders': error_orders, 'total_revenue': total_revenue}

My Initial Observations
I identified 3 responsibilities. AI found 6. The function was doing twice as much as I spotted.

Responsibility	I spotted it?
Validate inventory availability	Yes
Validate customer existence	Yes
Calculate base price with discount	Partially
Calculate shipping cost	No
Calculate tax	No
Build result and track revenue	No

Refactored Code
def validate_order(order, inventory, customer_data):
    """Check if order can be fulfilled. Returns error string or None."""
    if order['item_id'] not in inventory:
        return 'Item not in inventory'
    if inventory[order['item_id']]['quantity'] < order['quantity']:
        return 'Insufficient quantity'
    if order['customer_id'] not in customer_data:
        return 'Customer not found'
    return None

def calculate_item_price(item_id, quantity, customer_id, inventory, customer_data):
    """Calculate price with premium discount applied."""
    base_price = inventory[item_id]['price'] * quantity
    if customer_data[customer_id]['premium']:
        return base_price * 0.9
    return base_price

def calculate_shipping(price, customer_id, customer_data):
    """Calculate shipping based on customer location."""
    if customer_data[customer_id]['location'] == 'domestic':
        return 5.99 if price < 50 else 0
    return 15.99

def calculate_tax(price):
    """Apply standard 8% tax rate."""
    return price * 0.08

def process_orders(orders, inventory, customer_data):
    """Main function — coordinates smaller focused functions."""
    results, error_orders, total_revenue = [], [], 0
    for order in orders:
        error = validate_order(order, inventory, customer_data)
        if error:
            error_orders.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'error': error})
            continue
        item_id, quantity, customer_id = order['item_id'], order['quantity'], order['customer_id']
        price = calculate_item_price(item_id, quantity, customer_id, inventory, customer_data)
        shipping = calculate_shipping(price, customer_id, customer_data)
        tax = calculate_tax(price)
        final_price = price + shipping + tax
        inventory[item_id]['quantity'] -= quantity
        results.append({'order_id': order['order_id'], 'final_price': final_price})
        total_revenue += final_price
    return {'processed_orders': results, 'error_orders': error_orders, 'total_revenue': total_revenue}

What Improved
•	process_orders() went from 50 lines to 15 lines
•	Each function does exactly ONE thing — easy to test individually
•	Tax rate (0.08) and discount (0.9) are visible — easy to change
•	validate_order() can be reused elsewhere in the codebase

Exercise 3: Code Duplication Detection (JavaScript)
Original Code
function calculateUserStatistics(userData) {
  let totalAge = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < userData.length; i++) { totalAge += userData[i].age; }
  const averageAge = totalAge / userData.length;
  let totalIncome = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < userData.length; i++) { totalIncome += userData[i].income; }
  const averageIncome = totalIncome / userData.length;
  let totalScore = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < userData.length; i++) { totalScore += userData[i].score; }
  const averageScore = totalScore / userData.length;
  let highestAge = userData[0].age;
  for (let i = 1; i < userData.length; i++) {
    if (userData[i].age > highestAge) highestAge = userData[i].age;
  }
  let highestIncome = userData[0].income;
  for (let i = 1; i < userData.length; i++) {
    if (userData[i].income > highestIncome) highestIncome = userData[i].income;
  }
  let highestScore = userData[0].score;
  for (let i = 1; i < userData.length; i++) {
    if (userData[i].score > highestScore) highestScore = userData[i].score;
  }
  return { age: { average: averageAge, highest: highestAge },
           income: { average: averageIncome, highest: highestIncome },
           score: { average: averageScore, highest: highestScore } };
}

My Initial Observations
I spotted 2 repeated patterns. AI found 6 — three average loops and three highest-value loops, one for each field.

Pattern	Times Repeated	Fields
Average calculation loop	3	age, income, score
Highest value finder loop	3	age, income, score
Total loops in original code	6	90 lines of near-identical code

Refactored Code — Junior Developer Friendly Version
function calculateAverage(data, field) {
    let total = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
        total += data[i][field];
    }
    return total / data.length;
}

function findHighest(data, field) {
    let highest = data[0][field];
    for (let i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
        if (data[i][field] > highest) {
            highest = data[i][field];
        }
    }
    return highest;
}

function calculateUserStatistics(userData) {
    return {
        age: {
            average: calculateAverage(userData, 'age'),
            highest: findHighest(userData, 'age')
        },
        income: {
            average: calculateAverage(userData, 'income'),
            highest: findHighest(userData, 'income')
        },
        score: {
            average: calculateAverage(userData, 'score'),
            highest: findHighest(userData, 'score')
        }
    };
}

Benefits of Refactoring
•	90 lines reduced to 30 — 67% less code
•	Adding a new field (e.g. weight) requires ONE line, not 20
•	A bug fix in average calculation fixes ALL fields at once
•	Junior developers: simpler for-loops are more readable than reduce()
•	Two helper functions are individually testable

Comparison and Key Learnings
My Observations vs AI Findings
Exercise	What I Spotted	What AI Found Extra
Java readability	Names were unclear	SQL injection vulnerability, stream() pattern
Python refactoring	3 responsibilities	6 responsibilities — shipping and tax missed
JavaScript duplication	2 repeated patterns	6 loops — 3 average + 3 highest

Key Learnings
•	Unreadable names hide security bugs — the SQL injection in Exercise 1 was invisible until names were clarified
•	Functions doing too much are hard to test — each of the 6 responsibilities in process_orders needs its own test
•	Duplication is harder to spot than expected — I only found 2 of 6 repeated patterns
•	Readability and security are connected — clear code makes vulnerabilities obvious
•	AI spots patterns humans miss after staring at code too long

